          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Ninety percent of epistaxis episodes arise from Kiesselbach's plexus. Where is this plexus located?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Posteroinferior nasal septum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Posterior nosebleeds originate from the sphenopalatine artery in the posteroinferior region, but these account for only 10% of epistaxis and require endoscopic ligation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Anteroinferior nasal septum</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Kiesselbach's plexus (Little's area) lies at the anteroinferior nasal septum, where five arteries converge. Its superficial position and rich vascularity make it the commonest site of nosebleeds.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lateral wall near the middle turbinate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The middle turbinate region contains the ostiomeatal complex — the key drainage unit of the paranasal sinuses — but it is not the typical site of epistaxis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Roof of the nasal cavity near the cribriform plate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The roof is formed by the cribriform plate of the ethmoid. While the anterior ethmoidal artery runs here, it is not the commonest site for nosebleeds.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The answer is the anteroinferior nasal septum. Kiesselbach's plexus (Little's area) forms here from five converging arteries, making it the commonest site of epistaxis."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. Little's area at the anteroinferior septum is where 90% of nosebleeds originate. These anterior bleeds are treated by cauterisation or nasal packing."
                }
              ],
