          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Ethmoidal sinusitis most commonly spreads to the orbit because:</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Ethmoidal sinusitis most commonly spreads to the orbit because:</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The anterior ethmoidal artery provides a direct vascular route to the orbit</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While the anterior ethmoidal artery does connect both regions, the primary route of spread is direct erosion through the paper-thin bony wall, not haematogenous seeding.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The ethmoidal ostium opens directly into the orbital cavity</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The ethmoidal sinuses drain into the nasal meatuses (anterior cells into the middle meatus, posterior cells into the superior meatus), not into the orbit.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The ethmoidal sinuses share a common mucosal lining with the periorbita</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The ethmoid and orbit have separate linings — periosteum and periorbita respectively. Spread occurs by bony erosion through the lamina papyracea, not mucosal continuity.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The lamina papyracea, a paper-thin bony plate, forms the lateral wall of the ethmoid</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The lamina papyracea is extremely thin and separates the ethmoidal air cells from the orbit. Infection easily erodes through it, causing orbital cellulitis or abscess.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The answer is the lamina papyracea. This paper-thin bony plate forming the lateral ethmoid wall is the reason ethmoidal sinusitis is the commonest cause of orbital complications."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The lamina papyracea ('paper-like plate') is so thin that ethmoidal infection erodes through it, directly reaching the orbit and causing orbital cellulitis."
                }
              ],
